🇵🇸 Georges Abdallah est un combattant communiste libanais qui a résisté à l’invasion de son pays, le Liban, par les troupes de l’occupant sioniste et qui a défendu la Résistance palestinienne. 

🇵🇸 Ce révolutionnaire n’a jamais rien renié de son engagement politique anti-impérialiste qu’il confirme encore aujourd’hui par son inébranlable volonté et son attachement indéfectible à la juste cause des peuples opprimés de Palestine, du Liban, et partout dans le monde.

🇵🇸 𝗖𝗲 𝗽𝗿𝗶𝘀𝗼𝗻𝗻𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝗽𝗼𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗾𝘂𝗲 𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗮𝗿𝗰𝗲́𝗿𝗲́ 𝗲𝗻 𝗙𝗿𝗮𝗻𝗰𝗲 𝗮𝘂 𝗰𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗿𝗲 𝗽𝗲́𝗻𝗶𝘁𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗶𝗮𝗶𝗿𝗲 𝗱𝗲 𝗟𝗮𝗻𝗻𝗲𝗺𝗲𝘇𝗮𝗻 (𝟲𝟱) 𝗱𝗲𝗽𝘂𝗶𝘀 𝟭𝟵𝟴𝟰. 𝗟𝗲 𝟮𝟰 𝗼𝗰𝘁𝗼𝗯𝗿𝗲 𝗽𝗿𝗼𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗶𝗻, 𝗶𝗹 𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗺𝗲𝗿𝗮 𝘂𝗻𝗲 𝟰𝟬𝗲 𝗮𝗻𝗻𝗲́𝗲 𝗱𝗲 𝗱𝗲́𝘁𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗮𝗹𝗼𝗿𝘀 𝗾𝘂’𝗶𝗹 𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗹𝗶𝗯𝗲́𝗿𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲 𝗱𝗲𝗽𝘂𝗶𝘀 𝟮𝟰 𝗮𝗻𝘀. 

🇵🇸 Aucune demande de libération ne lui a été accordée jusqu’à présent par l’État français malgré deux décisions de libération de Justice prononcées par un Tribunal d’Applications des Peines. 

🇵🇸 𝗔𝘂𝗰𝘂𝗻 𝗮𝗿𝗿𝗲̂𝘁𝗲́ 𝗱’𝗲𝘅𝗽𝘂𝗹𝘀𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗾𝘂𝗶 𝗰𝗼𝗻𝗱𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻𝗻𝗲𝗿𝗮𝗶𝘁 𝘀𝗮 𝗹𝗶𝗯𝗲́𝗿𝗮𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗻’𝗮 𝗲́𝘁𝗲́ 𝘀𝗶𝗴𝗻𝗲́ 𝗽𝗮𝗿 𝗹𝗲 𝗺𝗶𝗻𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗿𝗲 𝗱𝗲 𝗹’𝗜𝗻𝘁𝗲́𝗿𝗶𝗲𝘂𝗿 𝗲𝗻 𝗽𝗹𝗮𝗰𝗲.

🇵🇸 Aujourd’hui les voix et les forces qui se mobilisent pour exiger sa libération ne cessent de s’amplifier. Cette mobilisation est portée sur le plan national mais aussi international et elle fait désormais bouger les lignes. 

🇵🇸 Plus que jamais, l’exigence de la libération de notre camarade doit être défendue et réaffirmée mais non, comme l’affirme Georges Abdallah lui-même en quémandant sa liberté mais par la lutte et 𝗹’𝗲́𝘁𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗶𝘀𝘀𝗲𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗱’𝘂𝗻 𝘃𝗲́𝗿𝗶𝘁𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲 𝗿𝗮𝗽𝗽𝗼𝗿𝘁 𝗱𝗲 𝗳𝗼𝗿𝗰𝗲 𝗮̀ 𝘁𝗿𝗮𝘃𝗲𝗿𝘀 𝗱𝗲𝘀 𝗮𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻𝘀 𝗺𝗶𝗹𝗶𝘁𝗮𝗻𝘁𝗲𝘀 𝗽𝗮𝗿𝘁𝗼𝘂𝘁 𝗲𝘁 𝘀𝘂𝗿 𝘁𝗼𝘂𝘀 𝗹𝗲𝘀 𝗳𝗿𝗼𝗻𝘁𝘀. 

🇵🇸 C’est par cet élargissement de nos actions que nous parviendrons à contraindre l’État français à libérer notre camarade.

🇵🇸 𝗦𝗮𝗺𝗲𝗱𝗶 𝟮𝟭 𝗼𝗰𝘁𝗼𝗯𝗿𝗲 𝗽𝗿𝗼𝗰𝗵𝗮𝗶𝗻, 𝗻𝗼𝘂𝘀 𝗿𝗲𝘁𝗼𝘂𝗿𝗻𝗲𝗿𝗼𝗻𝘀 𝗽𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗹𝗮 𝟭𝟯𝗲 𝗳𝗼𝗶𝘀, 𝗲𝘅𝗶𝗴𝗲𝗿 𝗹𝗮 𝗹𝗶𝗯𝗲́𝗿𝗮𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗱𝗲 𝗻𝗼𝘁𝗿𝗲 𝗖𝗮𝗺𝗮𝗿𝗮𝗱𝗲, 𝗾𝘂𝗶 𝗮 𝗱𝗲́𝗽𝗼𝘀𝗲́ 𝗹𝗲 𝟴 𝗷𝘂𝗶𝗻 𝗱𝗲𝗿𝗻𝗶𝗲𝗿 𝘂𝗻𝗲 𝗱𝗶𝘅𝗶𝗲̀𝗺𝗲 𝗱𝗲𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗱𝗲 𝗱𝗲 𝗹𝗶𝗯𝗲́𝗿𝗮𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻-𝗲𝘅𝗽𝘂𝗹𝘀𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝘃𝗲𝗿𝘀 𝘀𝗼𝗻 𝗽𝗮𝘆𝘀 𝗹𝗲 𝗟𝗶𝗯𝗮𝗻. 

🇵🇸 L’an dernier, à la même époque, Georges Abdallah écrivait :
« Camarades et Ami·e·s, les diverses initiatives solidaires que vous avez développées dans cette campagne internationale depuis un mois, apporte un cinglant démenti à ceux et à celles qui misaient sur l’essoufflement de votre mobilisation. »

🇵🇸 Cette année, soyons encore plus nombreux et déterminés à venir crier haut et fort lors de ce rassemblement à Saint-Denis et devant la prison de Lannemezan : « 𝗚𝗲𝗼𝗿𝗴𝗲𝘀 𝗔𝗯𝗱𝗮𝗹𝗹𝗮𝗵, 𝘁𝗲𝘀 𝗰𝗮𝗺𝗮𝗿𝗮𝗱𝗲𝘀 𝘀𝗼𝗻𝘁 𝗹𝗮̀ ! ».

text: I took part in an interesting conference of The Israeli Committee Against House Demolitions (ICAHD). Here you can watch my and other presentations. I begin in minute 51:30: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kcz5XN-RQ4U Here it is as a written text: The Zionist left destroyed Palestine; The right will burry the Zionist enterprise? The Zionist movement was colonial and European from its inception. It succeeded managed to join the British, who sought to control the country, and turned the zionists into their settler arm. Settler colonialism in Palestine was implemented through the division of labor: the British were the colonial empire, and the Zionists were the settlers who put the plan into action. Since the 1920s, the Zionists "redeemed the land," meaning they bought land parcels exclusively for Jews and "conquered" them, which meant Jewish settled on these lands. This involved the displacement of Palestinian Arabs from these lands, who lived legally on them many years, even though they weren’t their owners. Most of the "pioneers" settlers in labor groups and kibbutzim in the 1920s and 1930s were leftists, including Hashomer Hatzair and others. The leadership of the Jewish community prior to the state (HaYishuv in Hebrew) was Ashkenazi secular and anti-religious, with elements of anti-Semitism (which also manifested itself in nowadays). The Zionist movement had no interest in the culture and history of the country and certainly not in its Palestinian inhabitants. The land was the place to conquer in order establish the Jewish national home. Hatred of Arabs, Orientalism, continued after the establishment of the state and towards Arab Jews too, with the concept of the melting pot whose goal was to civilize Arab Jews, that is, to turn them into Europeans and to eliminate their Arabness. Until 1948, the future of Palestine was uncertain, but with the UN Partition Resolution its fate was doomed. The Palestinians could not accept a plan that took away half of their land. Arab countries, Jewish communists and ultra-religious Jews opposed it, but the plan was accepted by the United Nations. From there, the land deteriorated into severe violence between Zionists and Palestinians. The power balance favored the Zionists, and also because Palestinians perceived the whole region as their home, they were expelled and lost their homes. The Zionists destroyed Palestine and took control of 78% of the land. This was all done under the leadership of the Zionist left. Despite the expulsion of 750,000 Palestinians, who were the majority of the land's inhabitants, and the establishment of a Jewish state, the Zionists in the Declaration of Independence promised peace with their Arab neighbors and safeguarding the rights of all inhabitants. These words were empty from the moment they were written, but they were good enough for the international community to support the new Jewish state. This support was partly motivated by anti-Semitic sentiments - a preference for Jews being away from Europe - and feelings of guilt over the Holocaust. As long as the left led the country and continued to promote the false narrative of seeking peace, the world supported Israel. Even during the Suez Crisis and the occupation of Sinai in 1956, Britain and France supported Israel. In 1967, Israel completed the occupation of Palestine, and immediately afterward, despite hesitations and debates, whether honest or not regarding withdrawal, established settlements in the West Bank. Again, it was the Labor Party that led the way. Still, as long as Israel conveyed that it desired peace within the framework of two states, the world accepted it. In 1977, a political turn-over occurred, and the right-wing came to power. Under Begin's leadership, the only significant Israeli de-colonial move took place: withdrawal of the Sinai Peninsula in exchange for peace with Egypt. Since the completion of the occupation in 1967 the settler movement Gush Emunim, led by rabbi Zvi Yehuda Kook, saw in the expansion to new territories as messianic sings and pushed to establish settlement in The West Bank and later in Gaza Strip. While the political left used the religious component as a mobilizing one, and that’s why the Uganda option was changed by "Eretz Israel", the hard core settling movement took it as their core project and got the support of Labor government to establish settlements. The governments of the right, and especially the current government, is pushing Israel towards a direction it has not attempted before. This direction was well articulated in the "Submission Plan" written by Bezalel Smotrich a few years ago. According to that plan, Israel would hack the hopes of the Palestinians for an independent state and take full control of the West Bank. It suggests that Palestinians should be encouraged to emigrate voluntarily from the "Land of Israel," with Israel providing generous economic support and vocational training for those who choose to leave. *إنا لله وإنا إليه راجعون* إنتقل إلى رحمته تعالى في قرية دير جرير / فلسطين " غالب محمد عمار" (ابو احمد) عم الاخوة مهند ومؤيد ومجد نايف عمار اللهم ارحمه وأحسن مدخله وتجاوز عن سيئاته وزد في حسناته وتقبله في الصالحين، واغسله بالماء والثلج والبرد، ونقّه من الذنوب والخطايا كما يُنقّى الثوب الأبيض من الدنس، وأبدله دارًا خيرًا من داره، وأهلًا خيرًا من أهله، وزوجًا خيرًا من زوجه، وأعذه من عذاب القبر، واجمعنا اللهم جميعًا في الفردوس الأعلى من الجنة، واللهم آجر أهله في مصيبتهم وارزقهم خيرًا منها. اللهم لا تحرمنا أجره ولا تفتنّا بعده يا ذا الجلال والإكرام. تقبل التعازي بعد غدًا السبت في مسجد بمبانو بين صلاتي المغرب والعشاء إن شاء الله. Inna lillahi wa Inna ilayhi Rajioun (to Allah we belong and to Him we shall return) We are sad to announce the passing of brother Ghalib Mohamed Ammar (Abu Ahmad) in Dir Jarir in Palestine. The *condolences* will be offered in shaa Allah at the Islamic Center of South Florida this coming Saturday, Oct 7th, 2023. May Allah shower him with His Mercy, and Grant him Jannatul Firdaous May Allah give his family serenity and patience. ICOSF: 1641 NW 15th St. Pompano Beach, FL 33069

Occupied Palestinian Town of Huwwara Under Attack Again – Developing Story‼️Last February, hundreds of Israeli settlers stormed the town of Huwwara, killing one Palestinian and wounding many others‼️Today, October 5, dozens of settlers, under the protection of the Israeli military, are back in Huwwara‼️ Dozens of Israeli Jewish settlers, along with a large number of Israeli soldiers, stormed on Thursday night the town of Huwwara, located near to the occupied West Bank city of Nablus. Thursday night, Israeli occupation forces stormed Huwwara, killing a young Palestinian man, the official Palestinian news agency WAFA reported. Israeli occupation forces reportedly imposed an extensive lockdown on Palestinian businesses in Huwwara and tightened their restrictions at military checkpoints around the city of Nablus. Later in the evening, the Palestinian Ministry of Health confirmed that a young Palestinian man was shot dead by Israeli occupation forces. His identity is yet to be confirmed. WAFA correspondent said that Israeli occupation forces opened fire at a young man after surrounding him in a building near the Zaytouna Roundabout in the town of Huwwara. The soldiers reportedly blocked access to ambulance crews, leaving the wounded young man bleeding to death, according to eyewitnesses, cited by WAFA. This is the third Palestinian killed in 24 hours by Israeli occupation forces’ gunfire. On Thursday morning, Huthayfah Fares, 27, and Abd al-Rahman Atta, 23, were shot dead in the village of Shufa, southeast of Tulkarm. The Israeli military raid on Huwwara was followed by the storming of the town by dozens of illegal Jewish settlers. According to Aljazeera Arabic, the ongoing assault on Palestinian homes and other properties by the settlers is happening under the protection of the Israeli military. This is a developing story and the Palestine Chronicle will keep its readers updated. https://www.palestinechronicle.com/palestinian-town-of-huwwara-under-attack-again-developing-story/

HỘI ĐỒNG BẢO AN LIÊN HỢP QUỐC HAY LÀ HỘI ĐỒNG BẢO KÊ ?

Chúng ta được rao giảng nhiều về chức năng, nhiệm vụ, tính nhân đạo, cán cân công lý khi Liên Hợp Quốc ra đời. Nhưng kể từ khi thành lập tổ chức này chỉ cho thấy nó là một hội đồng bảo kê của giới tư bản phương Tây, sân sau của Hoa Kỳ.

Quyền lực nhất trong tổ chức này phải kể đến 5 thành viên thường trực của Hội đồng Bảo an. Tuy nhiên mất hết 3 anh hội chị em bạn dì trong khối Nato. Kẻ luôn châm ngòi chiến tranh, xâm phạm chủ quyền quốc gia khắp thế giới với luận điệu chống độc tài, khủng bố. Liên Xô và sau này là Nga; quốc gia duy nhất thường xuyên phủ quyết các cuộc trừng phạt hay can thiệp nội bộ quốc gia khác của Mỹ thì lại đơn độc. Anh cuối cùng là Trung Quốc sáng nắng chiều mưa, giữa trưa sương mù luôn chơi trò hai mang.

Iraq, Yemen hay Syria đều bị chính Liên Hợp Quốc tiếp tay trở nên đổ nát, đau khổ nhất là Palestine ngoài bị Nato và Isarel dày xéo còn bị chính những thảm họa nhân đạo do Liên Hợp Quốc gây ra nhất là cưỡng hiếp phụ nữ, trẻ em. Cũng chính Liên Hợp Quốc mở màn se duyên cho thời kỳ chiến tranh lạnh kéo dài khiến bao quốc gia bị chia cắt.

Tuy vậy có một thành viên duy nhất trên thế giới đã từng từ chối nộp đơn vào Liên Hợp Quốc khi chưa thống nhất, sau này là bị cô lập, cấm vận đã một mình cô độc chống lại bầy lang sói. Đấu tranh giành độc lập thống nhất, anh dũng chiến đấu hy sinh vì sự tồn vong của láng giềng. Đó chính là nước Việt Nam Dân chủ Cộng hòa nay là Cộng hòa xã hội chủ nghĩa Việt Nam.

"LIÊN HỢP QUỐC: "Tụi tao không rảnh"!

Năm 1977, 1978 - dọc tuyến biên giới Tây Nam xảy ra hơn 40 vụ thảm sát do quân Khmer đỏ tiến hành với nhân dân Việt Nam. Vụ nhỏ vài ba chục mạng người, vụ trung bình cỡ vài ba trăm. Liên Hiệp quốc bình thản vô tư dù đã nhận nhiều tố cáo của chính phủ Việt Nam kèm theo hình ảnh làm bằng chứng. Họ bảo rằng: "Các bằng chứng khá mơ hồ, không có tính thuyết phục. Thậm chí, có thể là ngụy tạo. Đề nghị Việt Nam tỏ rõ thiện chí giải quyết tranh chấp về biên giới, lãnh thổ với Campuchia để tránh các bất hòa đáng tiếc"

Nhờ thái độ đó của Liên Hiệp quốc, cường độ & quy mô các vụ thảm sát tăng chóng mặt : Thiện Ngôn, Xa Mát, Lò Gò, Thiện Hưng, Hưng Phước, Vĩnh Tế... với 600 - 700 dân thường bị giết dã man mỗi vụ. Tháng 05/1978 - Việt Nam phản công, mang quân đánh sang biên giới. "Cả thế giới" nhảy đổng lên gào thét căm hờn: "Việt Nam xâm lược 1 nước có chủ quyền ! Việt Nam chà đạp trắng trợn lên các chuẩn mực quốc tế & công nhiên thách thức lương tri nhân loại..."

Mỹ - Trung họp kín lên kế hoạch "Trừng phạt tiểu bá Việt Nam". Trung Quốc dự định gửi 40 sư đoàn đến "giúp" Pol pot bảo vệ độc lập. Mỹ đưa các đơn vị ở Guam, Nhật Bản, Nam Triều Tiên nhảy dù xuống các tỉnh giáp ranh biên giới Việt Nam - Campuchia để "lập vùng đệm cách ly". Các đơn vị "Phục quốc" của Ngụy Việt Nam Cộng hòa được gấp rút thành lập, chuẩn bị để về Sài Gòn tiếp quản chính quyền từ tay cộng sản. Các bạn bè cùng phe XHCN cũng lớn giọng lên án Việt Nam như Trung Quốc, Triều Tiên. Vài nước hăng hái đòi gửi quân hoặc viện trợ vũ khí cho Khmer đỏ như Albania, Rumani, Ba Lan... Trước tình thế đó, Việt Nam đành lui binh, đầy tủi hờn và cay đắng. Cùng lúc đó, hơn 3.000 người dân ở Ba Chúc bị giết thảm khốc. Pol Pot tuyên bố cho Việt Nam "ăn bánh chưng chấm với máu". Việt Nam khẩn thiết mời Liên Hiệp quốc đến chứng kiến. Liên Hiệp quốc trả lời: "Tụi tao đéo rảnh !"

Tháng 11/1978, Mặt trận đoàn kết dân tộc cứu quốc Campuchia ra đời, chính thức gửi lời cầu cứu sự giúp đỡ tới chính phủ & nhân dân Việt Nam. "Danh" đã chính & "Ngôn" đã thuận, Việt Nam tổng công kích. Ngày 23 tháng 12 năm 1978, QĐND Việt Nam do tướng Lê Trọng Tấn chỉ huy tiến hành phản công trên toàn mặt trận, đến ngày 7/1/1979 vào Phnom Penh - nhanh hơn so với tính toán của cả Mỹ lẫn Trung Quốc. Lần này, "Cả thế giới" vẫn kịch liệt phản đối & cực lực lên án nhưng không còn cớ để can thiệp. Bọn đồ tể, đao phủ dã man tàn bạo nhất thế kỷ 20 đã bị tiêu diệt, thù đã được trả & công lý đã được thực thi. Nhưng Việt Nam rất đỗi cô đơn, thời điểm đó: bị bao vây cấm vận ngặt nghèo, kinh tế sau 2 cuộc chiến tranh dài 30 năm vốn đã kiệt quệ, lại phải duy trì thêm mấy triệu quân chiến đấu trên 2 đầu biên giới.

Hơn 25 năm sau, thế giới văn minh mới rụt rè thừa nhận: Pol pot phạm tội diệt chủng. 

Việt Nam hiện nay chưa đủ tiếng nói để đại diện lương tri và lẽ phải. Bởi còn phải bảo vệ chính dân tộc ta. Nhưng có thể nói từng ngày khiến vị thế, dấu ấn trên trường quốc tế càng tăng. Việt Nam luôn hòa nhập chứ quyết không hòa tan. Chúng ta từng cô độc nhất nhưng bây giờ cũng là quốc gia duy nhất có thể làm bạn với toàn thế giới.

Chỉ vì một lọ muối Liên Hợp Quốc và Tây lông hủy diệt cả Iraq. Vậy mà Việt Nam chết hàng trăm ngàn nhân mạng đầy đủ bằng chứng chúng cho đó là ngụy tạo. Chúng ta thế hệ hôm nay gác đau thương hướng tới hiện tại tương lai nhưng tuyệt đối đừng bao giờ quên những năm tháng dân tộc bị dày vò đến tận cùng đó.

Đừng so sánh Việt Nam với bất kỳ ai. Thế hệ đi trước đã (truncated)

Fifty years ago today, a war erupted in the Middle East that changed not just the region, but the world. It’s a war of many names, depending on who you ask: the October War, the Yom Kippur War, the Ramadan War, or the 1973 Arab-Israeli War.⁠
.⁠
The war’s victor is just as disputed. It began with a two-pronged attack against Israel by Egypt and Syria.⁠
Egypt attacked from the south, to take back the Sinai Peninsula, and Syria from the north, to take back the Golan Heights.⁠
.⁠
Israel had captured both six years prior in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war, alongside occupying what remained of historic Palestine.⁠
.⁠
The recently formed state was riding high on that victory: it never anticipated an attack like this, especially not during Yom Kippur, an auspicious day for Jews. Meanwhile, the politics of the Cold War played in the background.⁠
.⁠
The Soviets supplied the Arab countries with weapons and the United States backed Israel. The two sides were on the brink of military conflict for the first time since the so-called Cuban Missile Crisis in 1962.⁠
.⁠

South Africans of faith must acknowledge that Israeli policies towards Palestinians are a carbon copy of the apartheid-era policies in South Africa or risk becoming complicit in the subjugation of Palestinians, the leader of the Anglican Church of Southern Africa (ACSA) has said.

In a statement released on 29 September, Thabo Makgoba, the Anglican Archbishop of Cape Town, said that the Church had recognised Israel as an apartheid state.

“As people of faith who are distressed by the pain of the occupation of the West Bank and Gaza - and who long for security and a just peace for both Palestine and Israel - we can no longer ignore the realities on the ground,” Makgoba said.

“Our hearts ache for our Christian brothers and sisters in Palestine, whose numbers include Anglicans but are rapidly declining. People of all faiths in South Africa have both a deep understanding of what it is to live under oppression,” he continued, before comparing Israel to South Africa under apartheid rule.

“When black South Africans who have lived under apartheid visit Israel, the parallels to apartheid are impossible to ignore. If we stand by and keep quiet, we will be complicit in the continuing oppression of the Palestinians,” Makgoba added.

While the South African Zionist Organisation lashed out at the resolution, with its chairperson calling the resolution "appalling" and "antisemitic" - other civil society groups like the Palestine Solidarity Committee and South African BDS Coalition, warmly welcomed the decision.

The Anglican Church said its stance was not an attack on Jewish people, "but to the policies of Israelis' governments, which are becoming ever more extreme".

"We salute the Anglican Church for not only calling out Israeli apartheid but also taking action,” South Africa's BDS Coalition said.

"The Anglican Church of Southern Africa is standing on the right side of history, fully supporting the Palestinian struggle for equality, human rights and justice," the coalition added.

The UN's special rapporteurs and several human rights organisations, such as Amnesty International, have concluded that Israel practises apartheid

The Biden administration has requested waivers for 26 environmental laws to speed the construction of the U.S.-Mexico border wall in Texas. 

The request, entered into the federal registry Wednesday by the Department of Homeland Security, seeks to circumvent the National Environmental Policy Act; the Clean Air Act; the Safe Drinking Water Act; the Endangered Species Act; and the Native American Graves Protection and Repatriation Act, among others. 

It's the first time President Biden has used his authority under the REAL ID Act to waive environmental laws, a power established in 2005 previously used by Trump and George W. Bush to build the border wall. 

In a statement the Center for Biological diversity said, "Every acre of habitat left in the Rio Grande Valley is irreplaceable. We can’t afford to lose more of it to a useless, medieval wall that won’t do a thing to stop immigration or smuggling. President Biden’s cynical decision to destroy a wildlife refuge and seal the beautiful Rio Grande behind a grotesque border wall must be stopped.”

Le cri de liberté de Chagall à La Piscine

Au fil d’une vie traversée par deux guerres et un exil, Marc Chagall (1887-1985) est à l’origine d’un oeuvre puissamment ancré dans l’histoire du XXe siècle. Figure du déplacement et de la migration, à l’instar de celles présentes dans son oeuvre, l’artiste sillonne le monde au gré des tourments du siècle, de son enfance en Russie à la France, de ses séjours en Allemagne à ceux en Palestine et en Pologne, des États-Unis au Mexique, avant de s’installer en Méditerranée. Son art, empreint d’un profond humanisme, nourri par ses racines juives et par les expériences vécues, se fait le messager d’un engagement sans faille pour l’homme et ses droits, pour l’égalité et la tolérance entre les êtres.

Porté par un grand cri de liberté, il confronte l’oeil aux guerres affrontées et aux combats artistiques menés, retraçant les conflits et événements majeurs du XXe siècle. Transcendés par la force poétique et l’imaginaire, ses oeuvres et ses écrits témoignent avec force de ses convictions politiques, de ses engagements humanistes qui s’expriment via une symbolique spécifique, parfois avec un sens aigu de la dérision et de l’humour ancrés dans sa culture juive. Crayon et pinceau deviennent des armes de paix pour le peintre, reflétant les luttes d’un XXe siècle « forgé dans le feu ». Dessins et peintures révèlent ainsi l’idéalisme sans condition du « peintre témoin de son temps », sa foi inébranlable en l’harmonie et la paix universelle entre les hommes, créant des regards et des dialogues croisés sur l’histoire en train de s’écrire.

CHAGALL POLITIQUE. LE CRI DE LIBERTÉ

As only one of two Levantine states flanking the Mediterranean Sea, Lebanon's geographic location is of great interest to the various road, rail, and waterway connectivity projects emerging in West Asia - not only in connecting the region, but as a bridge between Asia and Europe.

A second look, however, reveals a massive land access problem for Lebanon, which can only be reached via the territories of Syria and Occupied Palestine. Clearly then, for Lebanon to actively participate in West Asian connectivity initiatives, it must establish robust links with either of these two countries.

While Palestine is not a practical or feasible option for the time being, Syria remains Lebanon's only territorial means for the import and export of goods. However, more than a decade of conflict in Syria, persisting foreign occupation of its territories, and US-imposed Caesar Act sanctions have posed immense challenges to historic Lebanese-Syrian political and economic relations.

#onthisdayinhistory The Yom Kippur War began with an Egyptian and Syrian attack on land held by Israel from the Six Day War on October 6, 1973. In 1967, Israel launched a preemptive strike against Egypt in the Six Day War and subsequently occupied the Sinai Peninsula, the entirety of Palestine, and the Golan Heights. The capture of the Sinai Peninsula was a massive blunder for Egypt as they had to shut down the Suez Canal in its entirety. The war ended with both sides agreeing to a ceasefire. 

Both Egyptian and Syrian military planners saw a window of opportunity to attack Israel due to the ongoing Jewish holiday of Yom Kippur. Egypt in particular hoped to capture the eastern bank of the Suez Canal in order to leverage Israel into giving back the occupied Sinai Peninsula. As Egyptian forces advanced into the Sinai Peninsula, Syrian forces attacked the Israeli-occupied Golan Heights. After three days of heavy fighting, Israel halted the Egyptian advance and pushed Syria back to the pre-war ceasefire line. Israel then launched a four-day counteroffensive into Syria and managed to start shelling the Syrian capital of Damascus. Egyptian forces attempted a breakout, but failed and Israeli forces then pushed into Egypt. An October 22 United Nations brokered ceasefire fell apart, with each side blaming the other. As the Israelis pushed more and more towards the Egyptian capital of Cairo, tensions between the US (who supported Israel) and the Soviet Union (who supported Egypt) rose as well. A second ceasefire was imposed on October 25, which was far more successful and ended the war. 

The Yom Kippur War had some long-reaching impacts. Despite facing yet another humiliating defeat from Israel, the Arab powers did feel some sense of vindication with their early successes. Israel also accepted the fact that there may come a time when their military is not as dominant as previously believed. Both of these changes led to the beginning of an Israeli-Palestinian peace process and the 1978 Camp David Accords, where Israel agreed to give the Sinai Peninsula back to Egypt in exchange for Egypt recognizing Israel as a legitimate state. #yomkippurwar #israel #egypt #syria

At least 80 people were killed in a drone attack on the Military Academy in Homs on Thursday, during a cadet graduation ceremony, according to official Syrian media. The Syrian Ministry of Health announced that the death toll had risen to 89, with 277 injured.

The attack occurred at the end of the ceremony, according to the Syrian Observatory for Human Rights (SOHR), which estimated that 123 were killed, including 54 civilians, and 150 wounded.

The Syrian government declared three days of national mourning. Foreign Minister Faisal Mekdad spoke with Iranian Foreign Minister Hossein Amir-Abdollahian, who condemned the attack, according to SANA. Condemnations were also issued by the Sultanate of Oman, the United Arab Emirates, the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, the Islamic Jihad Movement in Palestine, and the General Conference of Arab Parties.

While no party has claimed responsibility, the Syrian Ministry of Foreign Affairs accused “terrorist organizations supported by the American occupation and other international parties, united in shedding Syrian blood.” Media outlets close to the Syrian regime indirectly accused the “Turkistan Islamic Party”, and the regime’s army announced the bombing of the party’s headquarters in Idlib and the Aleppo countryside, as well as those of the Muhajireen Battalion. These are the two factions possessing drone technology, according to sources who spoke to the Al-Alam News Network.

In response, Syrian forces targeted towns in Idlib Governorate and the western countryside of Aleppo, killing eight, according to SOHR. The White Helmets said on their Facebook pages that a bombing on the town of Kafr Nouran killed five civilians, wounding others. The bombing of Darat Izza killed three civilians and wounded more than ten, while a bombing on Sarmin led to one death and wounded others.

The northwestern fronts have seen an escalation recently, due to attempts by regime and opposition forces to advance on contact lines in the countryside of Latakia and Idlib. Regime forces’ attacks on the region in recent weeks have killed 63 civilians, including 11 children, and injured more than 280 others.

RAMALLAH, Palestine (AFP) - A Palestinian was martyred early Friday during clashes with Israeli soldiers and settlers in a town that has been the scene of frequent violence in the occupied West Bank, multiple sources said.

"Labib Mohammad Labib Dmidi, 19, was shot in the heart by settlers in the town of Huwara," the Palestinian health ministry said in a brief statement.

The Israeli army said in a statement that a suspect had been shot by soldiers, and a military spokesman said later he was unable to confirm whether the Palestinian had been killed or wounded.

Israeli occupation forces abducted, on Thursday, at least thirteen Palestinian young men in various regions of the occupied West Bank.

According to the Palestinian Prisoners’ Society (PPS), occupation forces abducted Iyad Omar Amara, 35, a resident of Tulkarem, while he was passing through the “Sarra” military roadblock west of the northern West Bank city of Nablus.

Ramallah and Al-Biereh governorate, in the central occupied West Bank, occupation forces abducted Muhammad Abd al-Hadi Samara, 21, Issa Hamad Muhammad Hamad, 20, and Abu Rahma, 21, after invading and searching their homes in Bil’in village, west of Ramallah.

Soldiers invaded the home of the young man, Imad Abu Alia, 20, in Al-Mughayir village, northeast of Ramallah, before abducting him.

In the city of Al-Biereh, occupation forces stormed an Palestinian-owned exchange shop belonging to Muhammad Al-Kok, seized money, abducted its manager and caused damage to the shop.

According to the shop’s owner, Israeli forces abducted the manager of the shop, identified as Muhammad Omar, a citizen of Rafat village northwest of occupied Jerusalem.

He added that soldiers confiscated money from the shop and vandalized its contents, causing damage, and noted that this is the second time in a week that the army has attacked his shops.

On Thursday night, a paramilitary Israeli colonizer killed a young Palestinian man in Huwwara town, south of Nablus, in the occupied West Bank’s northern part; four Palestinians, including two in Huwwara, have been killed by Israeli fire Thursday.

Medical sources said dozens of paramilitary colonizers stormed the town and started attacking cars, shops, and homes, leading to protests, before a colonizer shot Labib Mohammad Labib Dmeidi, 19.
The Palestinian Red Crescent Society (PRCS) said Mohammad was rushed to Rafidia Hospital in Nablus, suffering a gunshot wound to the heart, and succumbed to his injuries.

The PRCS added that 25 Palestinians, including four children, suffered the effects of tear gas inhalation and that the soldiers attacked a young man and prevented its medics from reaching him.

1st Reading: Baruch 1:15-22

The book of Baruch is attributed to Baruch, son of Neriah, the scribe who served Jeremiah the Prophet (Jer 32:12) and who wrote down his words (Jer 36:4).  Most scholars date it to the late second to mid-first century BC. 

According to its introduction (see 1:1-14), it was written in Babylon by Baruch after the deportation and sent to Jerusalem to be read at liturgical gatherings. The opening verses of this book ascribe it, or at least its first part, to Baruch, well-known as the secretary of the prophet Jeremiah. It contains five very different compositions, the first and the last in prose, the others in poetic form. The prose sections were certainly composed in Hebrew, though the earliest known form of the book is in Greek. 

Today, we have the first of two readings from the book. It is the beginning of what is called The Prayer of the Exiles, the exiles being those Jews who were deported to Babylon from Judah and Jerusalem by King Nebuchadnezzar in the 6th century BC. As the passage seems to belong to a much later date, it may rather reflect the feelings of a later community who saw in their own situation a similarity with those exiles. 

The details he gives indicate the year 582 BC, probably in the fifth month, the anniversary of the fall of Jerusalem, which was doubtless commemorated among the exiles as it was in Palestine The passage is a general lament for the situation of the Israelites now living in exile, far from their homeland and from Jerusalem and its Temple, the home of Yahweh. But there is no complaint against Yahweh for their condition. Their sufferings are due to one reason and one reason only – the people’s long history of not obeying the Lord and going their own way. This began from the days the Lord brought them out of Egypt right up to the present time. 

The writer compares the goodness and the integrity of God with that of his people. If they have suffered by being sent into exile, it is the result of their own sins and not the doing of the good God. In our response to this reading, we might reflect on how much of our own pain and misfortunes can be traced to our own behavior, individually or corporately.

NON XVi (UK) @non.xvi_official
O LITTLE TOWN OF BETHLEHEM
16x20" oil on canvas. 
Featured in our October 21st group show 
MAKE❤️NOT WAR 
Inquiries welcome. 

Listening to Christmas carols, watching footage of missile strikes in Bethlehem, and Ukraine, and imagining a new born baby, in a shed, and a newly delivered mother cradling her child against the bullets and shrapnel.
Their only protection is a blessing. 
Taking influence from Raphael and Da Vinci, a chubby cherub protects them from the silent stars.

@radioalhara راديو الحارة - Interview with artist Helena Martin Franco

https://soundcloud.com/freecityradio/radio-alhara-interview-with-artist-helena-martin-franco

Broadcast today, Oct. 6th at 3pm in Bethlehem, Palestine and 8am eastern time. Also aired in the past month on both @ckutmtl 90.3 FM and @cjlo1690am, broadcast times on write up at bottom.

An interview with artist and activist Helena Martin Franco @frittacaro. In this exchange Helena speaks about the process and the ideas behind the show Freehand Absence/Ausencia a mano alzada that showed in summer 2023 at the PHI Foundation for Contemporary Art. This show explores the silences in Helena's family past but also the ways that silences surrounding injustices, particularly relating to gender based violence, are embodied and carried across generations. Information on the show and Helena's work here: helenamartinfranco.com

The accompanying image is a section of a photograph taken by Richard-Max Tremblay of the exhibition by Helena in question.

Music on this edition is Passage by Anarchist Mountains.

Stefan contributes artist interviews to @radioalhara in Palestine that broadcast on the first Friday of each month at 10:30am eastern time, 5:30pm in Palestine (www.radioalhara.net). Also these interviews air on the third Friday of each month at 11am on @ckutmtl 90.3FM in Montreal (ckut.ca) and on the second Tuesday of each month on @cjlo1690am at 1:30pm also in Montreal.

Nebuchadnezzar II (r. 605-562 BC); known as the greatest king of the Chaldean Dynasty (626-539 BC) of Babylonia. He conquered Syria and Palestine and made Babylon a splendid city.

In 587 BC, Nebuchadnezzar destroyed the Kingdom of Judah, and its capital, Jerusalem. The destruction of Jerusalem led to the Babylonian captivity as the city's population, and people from the surrounding lands, were deported to Babylonia.

Because Babylon, well within his own territory, had been the target of most of his military campaigns and had caused the death of his son, Sennacherib destroyed the city in 689 BC.

In Mythology :

Nebuchadnezzar II was noted for conquering one of greatest djinn of the ancient world, King Solomon. However he was unpopular because after he did so, Nebuchadnezzar destroyed Jeruselam and stole the Solomon's Grimoire. King Nebuchadnezzar built the Ishtar Gate in Babylon in the honor of the first Blue Djinn, but in his self-pride he also built himself a magnificant palace. This angered the Blue Djinn because he built himself a greater palace than her own.

As a punishment, he is forced to stay in the Iravotum and has been there for millennia. He only survives because he, literally, has nothing to be desired. In John's travels in the Iravotum to rescue his sister, he meets him. he also thinks grass is regular food.

(The Children of the Lamp)

Fight Back News Service is circulating the following October 3 statement from the U.S. Palestinian Community Network (USPCN).

Normalization with the racist, settler-colonialist, zionist entity of Israel often begins with a U.S. directive aimed at Arab regimes, as evidenced by the first attempt with the Camp David Accords in 1978, which led to a “peace” agreement between Egypt and Israel. In essence, normalization coerces Arab regimes in the region to accept their subjugated status as compliant agents, which serves the zionist agenda and its U.S. imperialist patron. In light of the fast pace of change in today’s world order, the U.S. finds it necessary to push for normalization in order to maintain its global, imperialist dominance over Arab nations and thwart their progress toward independent, modern democracies.

Therefore, the current Saudi Arabian (and previous efforts like the Abraham Accords and others) push towards normalization with the zionist enemy fundamentally signifies a recognition of the settler-colonialist state’s legitimacy and an attempt to erase our people's historical and national rights in all of Palestine. Any discussion about the so-called “two-state solution” is nothing but an attempt to stall and buy time to create new realities on the ground that will be impossible to reverse. This is when submission, surrender, and betrayal become the inherent traits of Saudi Arabia or any other Arab regime that normalizes relations with Israel. The Saudis and the other normalizers have always supported the repression of the Palestine national liberation movement, and believe that peace deals with Israel will eventually quell Palestinian resistance and bring quiet and “stability” to the region. ... For this year’s festival, TIFF presents “Alam,” directed by Firas Khoury. 

Tamer and his friends lead a typical Palestinian student's life until the beautiful Maysaa arrives. To please her, Tamer agrees to take part in a mysterious operation on the eve of Israel's Independence Day, a mourning day for Palestinians.

Save the date— “Alam” will screen at this year’s Teaneck International Film Festival. Catch it on Sunday, November 12th at 11:30am at Teaneck Cinemas.

Posted @withregram • @aljazeeraenglish Fifty years ago today, a war erupted in the Middle East that changed not just the region, but the world. It’s a war of many names, depending on who you ask: the October War, the Yom Kippur War, the Ramadan War, or the 1973 Arab-Israeli War.⁠
.⁠
The war’s victor is just as disputed. It began with a two-pronged attack against Israel by Egypt and Syria.⁠
Egypt attacked from the south, to take back the Sinai Peninsula, and Syria from the north, to take back the Golan Heights.⁠
.⁠
Israel had captured both six years prior in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war, alongside occupying what remained of historic Palestine.⁠
.⁠
The recently formed state was riding high on that victory: it never anticipated an attack like this, especially not during Yom Kippur, an auspicious day for Jews. Meanwhile, the politics of the Cold War played in the background.⁠
.⁠
The Soviets supplied the Arab countries with weapons and the United States backed Israel. The two sides were on the brink of military conflict for the first time since the so-called Cuban Missile Crisis in 1962.⁠
.⁠

Posted @withregram • @middleeasteye South Africans of faith must acknowledge that Israeli policies towards Palestinians are a carbon copy of the apartheid-era policies in South Africa or risk becoming complicit in the subjugation of Palestinians, the leader of the Anglican Church of Southern Africa (ACSA) has said.

In a statement released on 29 September, Thabo Makgoba, the Anglican Archbishop of Cape Town, said that the Church had recognised Israel as an apartheid state.

“As people of faith who are distressed by the pain of the occupation of the West Bank and Gaza - and who long for security and a just peace for both Palestine and Israel - we can no longer ignore the realities on the ground,” Makgoba said.

“Our hearts ache for our Christian brothers and sisters in Palestine, whose numbers include Anglicans but are rapidly declining. People of all faiths in South Africa have both a deep understanding of what it is to live under oppression,” he continued, before comparing Israel to South Africa under apartheid rule.

“When black South Africans who have lived under apartheid visit Israel, the parallels to apartheid are impossible to ignore. If we stand by and keep quiet, we will be complicit in the continuing oppression of the Palestinians,” Makgoba added.

While the South African Zionist Organisation lashed out at the resolution, with its chairperson calling the resolution "appalling" and "antisemitic" - other civil society groups like the Palestine Solidarity Committee and South African BDS Coalition, warmly welcomed the decision.

The Anglican Church said its stance was not an attack on Jewish people, "but to the policies of Israelis' governments, which are becoming ever more extreme".

"We salute the Anglican Church for not only calling out Israeli apartheid but also taking action,” South Africa's BDS Coalition said.

"The Anglican Church of Southern Africa is standing on the right side of history, fully supporting the Palestinian struggle for equality, human rights and justice," the coalition added.

The UN's special rapporteurs and several human rights organisations, such as Amnesty International, have concluded that Israel practises apartheid

Third longest-serving Palestinian prisoner in Israel begins 39th year behind bars

Wafa
October 6, 2023

RAMALLAH, Friday, October 6, 2023 (WAFA) - Sixty-six-year-old Muhammad Altus, the third longest-serving Palestinian prisoner in Israel, began today his 39th year behind bars, according to the Palestinian Prisoner Society (PPS).

Altus, from Jabaa village in the south of the West Bank, was arrested on October 6, 1985 for resisting the Israeli occupation as part of Fatah fighters. He was shot and severely injured when he was arrested and then sentenced to life in prison.

His wife died in 2015 after being in a coma for one year and he has three children who were small when he was arrested but today are married and have brought him nine grandchildren, but they cannot visit him in prison because they are second-degree relatives.

According to the PPS, Altus is one of 26 Palestinians who have been in prison since before the signing of the Oslo peace accords in 1993 between the Palestine Liberation Organization and Israel and whom Israel has refused to set free in any prisoners’ release or exchange deal.

During his long years of detention, Altus was subjected to all forms of torture and acts of vengeance; aside from the serious injury he sustained during his arrest in 1985, he was subjected to harsh and long interrogations, his family home was demolished three times, and he was denied release in any prisoners' swap deal that were made during his incarceration, the latest of which was the prisoners swap of 2014, when Israel reneged on the release of the fourth batch of prisoners, which included Altus.

The first two longest-serving Palestinian resistance prisoners in Israel are Karim Younis, who has been behind bars for 38 years, and his cousin, Maher Younis, also 38 years behind bars, from the Palestinian town of Ara inside Israel.

फिलिस्तीन के प्रदर्शनकारी और इजरायली पुलिस के बीच आए दिन जेरुसलम और उसके आसपास के इलाके में झड़प होती रहती है.जेरुसलम एक ऐसा शहर है जहां इस्लाम, ईसाई और यहूदियों इन तीनों धर्म के लोगों की आस्था का केंद्र है. यहां अल-अक्सा मस्जिद है जो  मुसलमानों के लिए  मक्का और मदीना के बाद तीसरा सबसे पवित्र स्थान है.
इसी तरह ईसाइयों के लिए भी जेरुसलम सबसे पवित्र स्थलों में से एक है. यहां 'द चर्च ऑफ द होली सेपल्कर' है. मान्यता है कि जीसस को इसी जगह पर सूली पर चढ़ाया गया था और यहीं वे फिर से जीवित भी हुए थे. यहूदियों की ये भी मानता है कि यहां की वेस्टर्न वॉल उनके पवित्र मंदिर का अवशेष है.
आपको जानकारी के लिए बता दें कि इजरायल ने 1967 की लड़ाई में जेरुसलम के पूर्वी हिस्से पर कब्जा जमा लिया था. जिसके बाद इजरायल इसे अपनी राजधानी मानता चला आ रहा है. लेकिन अंतरराष्ट्रीय स्तर पर इसे मान्यता अब तक नहीं मिल पाई है इसलिए यहां किसी भी देश का दूतावास नहीं है यही वजह है कि तेल अवीव को पॉलिटिकल राजधानी माना जाता है.

النشيد الوطني الفلسطيني أو السَلام الوَطني الفلسطيني أَو نشيد فدائي من أناشيد الثورة الفلسطينية، اعتُمِد ليكون النشيد الوطني الرسمي للفلسطينيين بقرار من اللجنة التنفيذية لـمنظمة التحرير الفلسطينية سنة 1972 خلفاً لنشيد موطني الذي كان بمثابة النشيد الوطني غير الرسمي للفلسطينيين منذ عقد 1930. قامت حركة فتح بتغيير اسمه من "فدائي" إلى "نشيد الثورة الفلسطينية" في إطار حملتها لتحويل الأسماء الفتحاوية إلى أسماء فلسطينية عامة. صادق عليه مجلس الوزراء الفلسطيني في السلطة الوطنية الفلسطينية سنة 2005 ليصبح النشيد الرسمي لها.
